s franchises]]\n[[Category:Sega video games]]\n[[Category:Sega Saturn games]]\n[[Category:Sentai Filmworks]]\n[[Category:Steampunk video games]]\n[[Category:Video game franchises]]\n[[Category:Video game franchises introduced in 1996]]\n[[Category:Video games set in the 1920s]]\n[[Category:Tactical role-playing video games by series]]\n", "name_user": "ProtoDrake", "label": "safe", "comment": "citing uncited paragraph", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sakura_Wars"}
{"title_page": "Michael Schelp", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=February 2018}}\n'''Michael Schelp''' is an American writer and director, former producer of the 2008 television series ''[[Cha$e]]'', and former [[executive producer]] of ''[[MANswers]]''. Schelp founded the [[New York City|New York]]-based production company Spark Plug Entertainment in 2006. The company has created several [[mockbuster]] [[direct-to-video]] CGI films.\n\n==Career==\nMichel Schelp is the senior director of business affairs at Fujisankei Communications International, Inc. (FCI),<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.unicef.org/corporate_partners/japan_31710.html |title=UNICEF thanks Fuji TV for its longstanding support |first=Kun |last=Li |publisher=[[UNICEF]] |location=New York |date=March 17, 2006 |access-date=February 26, 2018}}</ref> a wholly owned subsidiary of Fuji Media Holdings, Inc., Japan's largest media conglomerate. FCI's sister companies include the Fuji Television Network, the Nippon Hoso Radio Network, Dinos Direct Marketing, Fusosha Publishing, Pony Canyon Music & Video, and ''Sankei Newspaper.''\n\nResponsible for developing and selling television content internationally, Schelp executive produced ''MANswers'' on Spike TV,<ref>{{Cite magazine |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/more-manswers-at-spike-157048 |title=More 'MANswers' at Spike |first=Kimberly |last=Nordyke |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |agency=AP |date=December 13, 2007 |access-date=February 26, 2018}}</ref> ''Blais Off'' on Discovery Science, ''Viking: the Ultimate Obstacle Course'' on ESPN, ''Reinventing the Meal'' on Cooking Channel, and ''SUPERCHEF KIDS'', a web series sponsored by P&G's Bounty. Schelp was a senior producer of ''CHA$E'' on SciFi Channel. He co-created, developed, and executive produced ''TILT 23 1/2'', an 86-episode reality TV series that has been licensed in over 120 countries. Schelp sold ''Iron Chef'' to the Food Network and manages FCI's business relationship with ABC News, CNN, and other American media organizations.\n\nSchelp is a member of the seven-person International Academy of Television Arts and Sciences Emmy Committee.\n\n==Spark Plug Entertainment==\nMichael Schelp is the president and chief executive officer of Spark Plug Entertainment, a New York-based studio that produces computer-animated features for the international home entertainment and television markets. In the United States, Spark Plug features on DVD are sold at Walmart, Kmart, and other leading retailers and aired on the Starz premium cable channel. Spark Plug has released fourteen titles: ''Bug Bites'' (a.k.a. ''Ant's Life''), ''Operation Dalmatian'', ''Mee Christmas'', ''Car's Life'', ''Plan Bee'', ''Spider's Web'', ''Piper Penguin and His Amazing Flying Machines'', ''Car's Life 2'', ''Toyz Goin' Wild'', ''The Adventures of Scooter the Penguin'', ''Car's Life 3: The Royal Heist'' and ''Car's Life 4: Junkyard Blues''.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Direct-to-video===\n*''Operation: Dalmatian - Fun With Letters'' (1998) (writer/director)\n*''[[Bug Bites: An Ant's Life]]'' (1998; re-released 2006) (writer/producer) (piggy-back on ''[[A Bug's Life]]'' and ''[[Antz]]'')\n*''[[Mee Christmas]]'' (2000) (writer/director)\n*''My Exotic Farm'' (2005) (writer/director/producer) (piggy-back on ''[[Madagascar (2005 film)|Madagascar]]'')\n*''[[A Car's Life: Sparky's Big Adventure (film)|A Car's Life: Sparky's Big Adventure]]'' (2006) (piggy-back on ''[[Cars (film)|Cars]]'')\n*''Spider's Web: A Pig's Tale'' (2006) (writer/director) (piggy-back on ''[[Charlotte's Web (2006 film)|Charlotte's Web]]'')\n*''Plan Bee'' (2007) (writer/director/producer) (piggy-back on ''[[Bee Movie]]'')\n*''An Ant's Life 2: The Insect Stories'' (2007) (piggy-back on ''[[A Bug's Life]]'' and ''[[Antz]]'')\n*''Sea Life Safari'' (2008) (writer/director/producer) (piggy-back on ''[[The Little Mermaid]]'')\n*''Piper Penguin and His Fantastic Flying Machines'' (2008) (piggy-back on ''[[Surf's Up (film)|Surf's Up]]'' and ''[[Happy Feet]]'')*\n*''Frankie Stein'' (2008) (Cancelled and currently lost)\n*''[[Car's Life 2]]'' (2012) (piggy-back on ''[[Cars 2 (film)|Cars 2]]'')\n*''The Adventures of Scooter the Penguin'' (2012) (writer/director/producer) (piggy-back to ''[[Happy Feet Two]]'')\n*''[[Car's Life 3: The Royal Heist]]'' (2013) (piggy-back on ''[[Cars 3 (film)|Cars 3]]'')\n*''[[Car's Life 4: Junkyard Blues]]'' (2014)\n\n===TV===\n*''[[Cha$e]]'' (6 episodes, 2008) (producer)\n*''[[MANswers]]'' (19 episodes, 2007\u20132010) (producer/executive producer)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0770810}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schelp, Michael}}\n[[Category:American film directors]]\n[[Category:American film producers]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=February 2018}}\n'''Michael Schelp''' is an American writer and director, former producer of the 2008 television series ''[[Cha$e]]'', and former [[executive producer]] of ''[[MANswers]]''. Schelp founded the [[New York City|New York]]-based production company Spark Plug Entertainment in 2006. The company has created several [[mockbuster]] [[direct-to-video]] CGI films.\n\n==Career==\nMichel Schelp is the senior director of business affairs at Fujisankei Communications International, Inc. (FCI),<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.unicef.org/corporate_partners/japan_31710.html |title=UNICEF thanks Fuji TV for its longstanding support |first=Kun |last=Li |publisher=[[UNICEF]] |location=New York |date=March 17, 2006 |access-date=February 26, 2018}}</ref> a wholly owned subsidiary of Fuji Media Holdings, Inc., Japan's largest media conglomerate. FCI's sister companies include the Fuji Television Network, the Nippon Hoso Radio Network, Dinos Direct Marketing, Fusosha Publishing, Pony Canyon Music & Video, and ''Sankei Newspaper.''\n\nResponsible for developing and selling television content internationally, Schelp executive produced ''MANswers'' on Spike TV,<ref>{{Cite magazine |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/more-manswers-at-spike-157048 |title=More 'MANswers' at Spike |first=Kimberly |last=Nordyke |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |agency=AP |date=December 13, 2007 |access-date=February 26, 2018}}</ref> ''Blais Off'' on Discovery Science, ''Viking: the Ultimate Obstacle Course'' on ESPN, ''Reinventing the Meal'' on Cooking Channel, and ''SUPERCHEF KIDS'', a web series sponsored by P&G's Bounty. Schelp was a senior producer of ''CHA$E'' on SciFi Channel. He co-created, developed, and executive produced ''TILT 23 1/2'', an 86-episode reality TV series that has been licensed in over 120 countries. Schelp sold ''Iron Chef'' to the Food Network and manages FCI's business relationship with ABC News, CNN, and other American media organizations.\n\nSchelp is a member of the seven-person International Academy of Television Arts and Sciences Emmy Committee.\n\n==Spark Plug Entertainment==\nMichael Schelp is the president and chief executive officer of Spark Plug Entertainment, a New York-based studio that produces computer-animated features for the international home entertainment and television markets. In the United States, Spark Plug features on DVD are sold at Walmart, Kmart, and other leading retailers and aired on the Starz premium cable channel. Spark Plug has released fourteen titles: ''Bug Bites'' (aka ''Ant's Life''), ''Operation Dalmatian'', ''Mee Christmas'', ''Car's Life'', ''Plan Bee'', ''Spider's Web'', ''Piper Penguin and His Amazing Flying Machines'', ''Car's Life 2'', ''Toyz Goin' Wild'', ''The Adventures of Scooter the Penguin'', ''Car's Life 3: The Royal Heist'' and ''Car's Life 4: Junkyard Blues''.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Direct-to-video===\n*''Operation: Dalmatian - Fun With Letters'' (1998) (writer/director)\n*''[[Bug Bites: An Ant's Life]]'' (1998; re-released 2006) (writer/producer) (piggy-back on ''[[A Bug's Life]]'' and ''[[Antz]]'')\n*''[[Mee Christmas]]'' (2000) (writer/director)\n*''My Exotic Farm'' (2005) (writer/director/producer) (piggy-back on ''[[Madagascar (2005 film)|Madagascar]]'')\n*''[[A Car's Life: Sparky's Big Adventure (film)|A Car's Life: Sparky's Big Adventure]]'' (2006) (piggy-back on ''[[Cars (film)|Cars]]'')\n*''Spider's Web: A Pig's Tale'' (2006) (writer/director) (piggy-back on ''[[Charlotte's Web (2006 film)|Charlotte's Web]]'')\n*''Plan Bee'' (2007) (writer/director/producer) (piggy-back on ''[[Bee Movie]]'')\n*''An Ant's Life 2: The Insect Stories'' (2007) (piggy-back on ''[[A Bug's Life]]'' and ''[[Antz]]'')\n*''Sea Life Safari'' (2008) (writer/director/producer) (piggy-back on ''[[The Little Mermaid]]'')\n*''Piper Penguin and His Fantastic Flying Machines'' (2008) (piggy-back on ''[[Surf's Up (film)|Surf's Up]]'' and ''[[Happy Feet]]'')*\n*''Frankie Stein'' (2008) (Cancelled and currently lost)\n*''[[Car's Life 2]]'' (2012) (piggy-back on ''[[Cars 2 (film)|Cars 2]]'')\n*''The Adventures of Scooter the Penguin'' (2012) (writer/director/producer) (piggy-back to ''[[Happy Feet Two]]'')\n*''[[Car's Life 3: The Royal Heist]]'' (2013) (piggy-back on ''[[Cars 3 (film)|Cars 3]]'')\n*''[[Car's Life 4: Junkyard Blues]]'' (2014)\n\n===TV===\n*''[[Cha$e]]'' (6 episodes, 2008) (producer)\n*''[[MANswers]]'' (19 episodes, 2007\u20132010) (producer/executive producer)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0770810}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schelp, Michael}}\n[[Category:American film directors]]\n[[Category:American film producers]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Vanisaac", "label": "safe", "comment": "Correcting spelling: aka->a.k.a.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Schelp"}
